le English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Andrzej, Grzegorz, Irena, Lucyna, Witold.","Polish (mainly <b>Łada</b>) and Czech (Moravian): from a short form of the Polish personal name <i>Ładysław</i>, Czech <i>Ladislav</i>, both from <i>Vladislav</i> (Latinized as <i>Ladislaus</i>), a Slavic name composed of the elements <i>vlad</i> ‘to rule’ (from Old Slavic <i>vlasti</i>, later <i>vladati</i>) + <i>slav</i> ‘glory’ or ‘famous’ (from <i>slava</i> ‘glory’). Compare 2 below.","Hungarian: from <i>Lad(a)</i>, a short form of the personal name <i>Ladomér</i>, a Hungarian form of Slavic <i>Vladimir</i> (see   Lado   2, compare 1 above)."]}]},{"name":"Stackpole","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Welsh: habitational name from Stackpole (Pembrokeshire), apparently named with Old Norse <i>stakkr</i> ‘stack’ + <i>pollr</i> ‘pool’, referring to a stack of rocks on the coast at the entrance to Broadhaven. The name was taken to Ireland and adapted by settlers of Norman descent, where it is recorded in Dublin as early as 1200. The name has been Gaelicized as <b>de Stacapúl</b>; the family was also known in Irish as <b>Galldubh</b> ‘dark stranger’."],"variants":[{"name":"Stackpoole","meanings":["English (Cheshire) and Welsh: variant of   Stackpole  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Isabelle Lady Stackpole was born in 1355, in Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales. She had at least 1 daughter with Rhys Ieuanc (Sir) Ap Rhys Hen. She died in 1380, at the age of 25."},"et":{"1355–1380":"1355–1380","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1363–1402":"1363–1402","1402":"1402","1355":"1355","1320":"1320","1363":"1363","1380":"1380","Coity, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fi":{"1355–1380":"1355–1380","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1363–1402":"1363–1402","1402":"1402","1355":"1355","1320":"1320","1363":"1363","1380":"1380","Coity, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales"},"fr":{"1355–1380":"1355–1380","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1363–1402":"1363–1402","1402":"1402","1355":"1355","1320":"1320","1363":"1363","1380":"1380","Coity, Glamorganshire, Wales":"Coity, Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Isabelle Lady Stackpole est née en 1355, à Stackpole Elidor, Pembrokeshire, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fille avec Rhys Ieuanc (Sir) Ap Rhys Hen. Elle est décédée en 1380, à l’âge de 25 ans."},"de":{"1355–1380":"1355–1380","1320–1380":"1320–1380","1363–1402":"1363–1402","1402